    <div id="notes-0">
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">What Is Insurance?</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p>Insurance = the <strong style="color:var(--text)">transfer of risk of loss</strong> from an individual to an insurance company, which spreads the cost among many people.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:7px">You pay a <strong style="color:var(--text)">premium</strong>. The insurer is contractually obligated to pay claims as long as all terms are met.</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Insurance transfers risk. Insurer spreads cost among all insureds.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Law of Large Numbers</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p>The <strong style="color:var(--text)">larger</strong> the pool of people with similar exposure, the more <strong style="color:var(--text)">predictable</strong> actual losses become. This is how premiums are calculated.</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Bigger pool = more predictable losses = fairer rates</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Insurable Interest</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p>You must stand to suffer a <strong style="color:var(--text)">financial loss</strong> if the insured property is damaged. In P&amp;C must exist <strong style="color:var(--amber)">at the time of the loss</strong>.</p>
          <ul><li>Financial (monetary stake)</li><li>Blood (family member)</li><li>Business (business partner)</li></ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Risk — Pure vs. Speculative</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Type</th><th>Outcome</th><th>Insurable?</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Pure Risk</td><td>Loss only, or no change</td><td style="color:var(--green)">✓ YES</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speculative Risk</td><td>Loss OR gain (gambling)</td><td style="color:var(--red)">✗ NO</td></tr></table>
          <div class="highlight">→ ONLY pure risks are insurable!</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">5 Elements of Insurable Risk</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ol><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Due to chance</strong> — accidental, not intentional</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Definite &amp; measurable</strong> — can be seen and quantified</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Statistically predictable</strong> — insurer can estimate frequency</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Not catastrophic</strong> — won't bankrupt the insurer</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Large loss exposure</strong> — enough people paying premiums</li></ol>
          <div class="highlight">→ War is excluded — it is CATASTROPHIC; all could claim at once</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Hazards — 3 Types</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Hazard</th><th>What It Is</th><th>Example</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Physical</td><td>Material/structural condition</td><td>Slippery floor</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Moral</td><td>Fraud / lying on application</td><td>Fake claims</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Morale</td><td>Careless because "I'm insured"</td><td>"It'll be covered"</td></tr></table>
          <div class="highlight">→ Moral = dishonesty. Morale = indifference. Watch spelling on exam!</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Peril vs. Hazard vs. Risk</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Risk</strong> = chance a loss WILL occur</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Hazard</strong> = increases the PROBABILITY of loss</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Peril</strong> = the actual CAUSE of the loss (fire, flood, theft)</li></ul>
          <div class="highlight">→ Risk → Hazard increases it → Peril causes loss → Insurance covers it</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Indemnity &amp; Subrogation</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p><strong style="color:var(--text)">Indemnity:</strong> Restores insured to same position as before loss. Collect only to extent of actual loss — <strong style="color:var(--amber)">no profiting from insurance</strong>.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:9px"><strong style="color:var(--text)">Subrogation:</strong> After paying you, insurer can sue the at-fault party. Prevents collecting twice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Property vs. Casualty Insurance</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Type</th><th>Covers</th><th>Contract</th><th>Pays</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Property</td><td>YOUR stuff</td><td>2-party</td><td>Policyowner</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Casualty/Liability</td><td>Damage to OTHERS</td><td>3-party</td><td>Third party</td></tr></table>
          <div class="highlight">→ Liability does NOT pay the policyowner — it pays the injured third party!</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Exposure vs. Loss</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
          <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--amber)">Exposure</strong></td><td>How likely it is that something bad might happen — people and property are at risk of loss purely by existing</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong style="color:var(--blue)">Loss</strong></td><td>The reduction, decrease, or disappearance of value</td></tr></table>
          <div class="highlight">→ Exposure = the RISK of loss existing. Loss = when the damage actually happens.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Accident vs. Occurrence</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Accident</td><td>Sudden, unexpected, single event</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Occurrence</td><td>Includes continuous/repeated exposure over time — broader</td></tr></table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Direct vs. Indirect Loss</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Direct:</strong> Physical damage to property itself</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Indirect (Consequential):</strong> Economic loss FROM the direct loss (extra living expenses, lost rent, lost profits)</li></ul>
          <p style="margin-top:9px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text3)">Fire damages home (direct). Water from hoses also covered — fire was the <strong style="color:var(--amber)">proximate cause</strong>.</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Property insurance covers direct losses. Indirect requires added coverage.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Named Peril vs. Open Peril</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Type</th><th>Coverage</th><th>Think of it as</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Named Peril</td><td>Only listed perils covered</td><td>"Only THIS"</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Open/Special Peril</td><td>Everything EXCEPT exclusions</td><td>"Anything BUT this"</td></tr></table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Burglary / Robbery / Theft</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Burglary</strong> = forced entry, <strong style="color:var(--amber)">visible signs required</strong></li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Robbery</strong> = taken by force/threat directly from a person</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Theft</strong> = umbrella term covering both + more</li></ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Vacancy vs. Unoccupancy</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Term</th><th>People?</th><th>Contents?</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Vacant</td><td style="color:var(--red)">✗ No</td><td style="color:var(--red)">✗ No</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Unoccupied</td><td style="color:var(--red)">✗ No</td><td style="color:var(--green)">✓ Yes</td></tr></table>
          <div class="highlight">→ 60 consecutive days of vacancy can void or reduce coverages!</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Negligence — 4 Elements</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ol><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Legal duty</strong></li><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Standard of care</strong> — must have breached it</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Proximate cause</strong> — unbroken chain from negligence to injury</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Actual loss or damage</strong></li></ol>
          <table class="mini-t" style="margin-top:12px"><tr><th>Type</th><th>Rule</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Contributory</td><td>Any fault by injured = NO recovery</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Comparative</td><td>Damages reduced by % of your fault</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Pure Comparative</td><td>Can recover unless 100% at fault</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Modified Comparative</td><td>Must be less at fault than defendant</td></tr></table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Loss Valuation Methods</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Method</th><th>Key Point</th><th>Depreciation?</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Replacement Cost</td><td>Like kind &amp; quality TODAY. Most generous.</td><td style="color:var(--green)">✗ None</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ACV</td><td>Replacement cost minus depreciation</td><td style="color:var(--red)">✓ Yes</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Functional Replacement</td><td>Modern materials — historic properties</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Market Value</td><td>Buyer pays seller — includes land &amp; location</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Agreed Value</td><td>Agreed upfront. Best for art/antiques.</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Stated Amount</td><td>Scheduled on declarations page. No coinsurance.</td><td>N/A</td></tr></table>
          <div class="formula">ACV = Replacement Cost − Depreciation</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Types of Liability</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Type</th><th>Key Point</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Absolute</td><td>Hazardous activity — no proof of negligence needed</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Strict</td><td>Defective products — prove defect = liable regardless of fault</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Vicarious</td><td>Employer liable for employee (respondeat superior)</td></tr></table>
          <p style="margin-top:11px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text3)"><strong style="color:var(--amber)">Ladder example:</strong> Advertised for 500 lbs, fails at 300 lbs → manufacturer strictly liable.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Limits of Liability + Aggregate Example</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="mini-t"><tr><th>Limit</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Per Occurrence</td><td>Cap on ALL claims from one event</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Per Person</td><td>Max for one person's bodily injury</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Aggregate</td><td>Annual max — resets at policy anniversary</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Split (25/50/25)</td><td>$25K/person · $50K/occurrence · $25K property</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Combined Single</td><td>One total for BI + PD combined</td></tr></table>
          <p style="margin-top:12px;font-size:0.8rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--amber)">◇️ Real Example: $1M per-occurrence / $2M aggregate</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2);margin-top:4px">Feb: Ceiling collapse → $1M paid → $1M left in aggregate<br>
          Jul: Fire causes $1.5M loss → only $1M paid (all that remains)<br>
          After Jul: <strong style="color:var(--red)">$0 aggregate — NO coverage</strong> until Jan 1, 2027</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Once aggregate is exhausted, no coverage until policy anniversary</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Proximate Cause — Chain of Events</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p>The <strong style="color:var(--text)">first negligent act</strong> that started an unbroken chain leading to injury/damage.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:9px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text3)">Driver runs red light → accident → utility pole down → power outage damages business. The <strong style="color:var(--amber)">red light violation</strong> is proximate cause of ALL damage.</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Proximate cause = the first negligent act in the chain</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Coinsurance Formula</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div class="formula">(Insurance Carried ÷ Insurance Required) × Loss = Payment</div>
          <p style="margin-top:11px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2)">Example: $100K building, 80% required = $80K needed. You carry $40K. Loss = $10K.<br>
          ($40K ÷ $80K) × $10K = <strong style="color:var(--amber)">$5,000 paid</strong>. You absorb the other $5,000.</p>
          <div class="highlight">→ Total loss = coinsurance doesn't apply. Face amount paid in full.</div>
          <div style="margin-top:12px;padding:12px 14px;background:rgba(155,127,199,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(155,127,199,0.25);border-radius:var(--r2)">
            <div style="font-size:0.7rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--purple);text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.6px;margin-bottom:7px">💡 Exam Tip — D before S</div>
            <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2);margin:0;line-height:1.7">
              <strong style="color:var(--text)">Only apply the formula if the insured is underinsured.</strong><br>
              To set up the fraction, remember: <strong style="color:var(--purple)">D comes before S</strong><br>
              — what they <strong style="color:var(--amber)">(D)id</strong> have goes on top ÷ what they <strong style="color:var(--amber)">(S)houldve</strong> had goes on bottom.<br>
              <span style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--text3)">Did = Insurance Carried &nbsp;|&nbsp; Shouldve = 80% of Replacement Cost</span>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Underwriting, Rate &amp; Loss Ratio</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Underwriting</strong> = risk selection at insurer's home office</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Rate</strong> = cost per unit of insurance</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Premium</strong> = actual dollar amount to keep policy in force</li></ul>
          <div class="formula">Loss Ratio = Losses Incurred ÷ Earned Premium</div>
          <p style="margin-top:10px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2)">$75K claims ÷ $150K premium = <strong style="color:var(--amber)">50% loss ratio</strong></p>
          <div class="highlight">→ HIGH loss ratio = poor underwriting = insolvency risk</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="concept">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">FCRA, Certificate &amp; Deposit Premium</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul><li><strong style="color:var(--text)">FCRA</strong> = administered by <strong style="color:var(--amber)">FTC</strong>. Protects consumers from inaccurate financial info.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Certificate of Insurance</strong> = proof a policy exists. Does NOT obligate insurer to holder.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">Deposit Premium Audit</strong> = insurer can audit up to <strong style="color:var(--amber)">3 years</strong> after expiration.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--text)">MedPay</strong> = no-fault coverage. No negligence proof needed.</li></ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div id="notes-1" style="display:none">

      <!-- TERMS TO KNOW -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Ch. 2 — Terms to Know</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="notes-table">
            <tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Appraisal</strong></td><td>A professional assessment to determine the extent of damage</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Earned Premium</strong></td><td>The portion of premium already paid that belongs to the insurer because it covers the elapsed part of the policy</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Liberalization</strong></td><td>The removal or loosening of restrictions; if insurer adds better free coverage, insured gets it immediately</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Negligence</strong></td><td>Failure to use the care a reasonable, prudent person would under the same circumstances</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Policyowner</strong></td><td>The person entitled to exercise the rights and privileges in the policy</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Third Party</strong></td><td>An individual or entity other than the two parties to the contract (insured and insurer)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Underwriting</strong></td><td>Risk selection; reviewing applications to determine eligibility for coverage</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 4 ELEMENTS OF A CONTRACT -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">4 Elements of a Valid Contract</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div class="formula">Agreement · Consideration · Competent Parties · Legal Purpose</div>
          <table class="notes-table" style="margin-top:12px">
            <tr><th>Element</th><th>What It Means</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Agreement</strong></td><td>Offer + Acceptance. Applicant makes the offer (submits application); insurer accepts by approving and issuing the policy</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Consideration</strong></td><td>Something of value from each side. <em>Insured:</em> premium payment + statements on application. <em>Insurer:</em> promise to pay in the event of loss</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Competent Parties</strong></td><td>Both parties must be of legal age, mentally competent, and not under the influence of drugs or alcohol</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Legal Purpose</strong></td><td>Contract must be for a lawful reason and not against public policy</td></tr>
          </table>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:10px">→ Memory: <strong>A.C.C.L.</strong> — Agreement, Consideration, Competent parties, Legal purpose</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- REPRESENTATIONS, WARRANTIES, CONCEALMENT -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Representations, Warranties &amp; Concealment</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="notes-table">
            <tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th><th>Effect if Violated</th></tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Representation</strong></td>
              <td>Statements believed to be true to the best of one's knowledge — NOT guaranteed to be true. The insured's answers on the application are representations.</td>
              <td>Untrue statements = <strong>misrepresentation</strong> → may void the contract. If intentional = <strong>fraud</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Warranty</strong></td>
              <td>An absolutely true statement upon which the validity of the policy depends. Much stricter than a representation.</td>
              <td>Breach of warranty = grounds for voiding policy or return of premium</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Concealment</strong></td>
              <td>Intentional withholding of material information that would affect the underwriting decision.</td>
              <td>May void the policy</td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:10px">→ <strong>Material misrepresentation</strong> = a statement that, if discovered, would change the insurer's underwriting decision. If intentional = fraud.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- BINDERS -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Binders</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul>
            <li>A <strong>binder</strong> is a temporary agreement providing coverage until a policy can be issued</li>
            <li>Can be written or <strong>verbal</strong></li>
            <li>Binder expires when the policy is <strong>issued</strong></li>
            <li>Policy effective date = same as the date the binder was issued</li>
            <li>If insurer <em>declines</em> to issue the policy → binder expires the day after receipt of cancellation notice</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- POLICY STRUCTURE -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Policy Structure — 7 Components</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div class="formula">Dec · Def · IA · Add · Cond · End · Excl</div>
          <table class="notes-table" style="margin-top:12px">
            <tr><th>Component</th><th>What It Contains</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Declarations</strong></td><td>First page. Insured's name, address, coverage amounts, premiums, description of insured location, supplemental representations</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Definitions</strong></td><td>Clarifies terms used in the policy. Bold/italic/quoted words have specific defined meanings</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Insuring Agreement</strong></td><td>The insurer's promise to provide coverage. Lists parties, effective dates, description of coverage, perils covered</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Additional Coverage</strong></td><td>Extra coverage for specific loss expenses at NO additional premium (e.g. defense expenses, protecting damaged property)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Conditions</strong></td><td>Rules both parties agree to follow. Includes: inspection rights, changes must be in writing, liberalization clause, return of premium method</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Endorsements</strong></td><td>Written addendums that change policy terms, conditions, or coverages. Must be in writing, attached to policy, signed by executive officer of insurer</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Exclusions &amp; Limits</strong></td><td>What is NOT covered. Can exclude people (except spouse), property, perils. Examples: earth movement, water damage (flood, sewer backup, subsurface water)</td></tr>
          </table>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:10px">→ Memory tip: <strong>"Did Destiny Insure Any Conditions? Endorsements Excluded"</strong></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TYPES OF INSUREDS -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Types of Insureds</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="notes-table">
            <tr><th>Type</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Insured</strong></td><td>Anyone covered under the policy — named or not. Includes unnamed spouse and resident relatives in household</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Named Insured</strong></td><td>The individual(s) whose name appears on the Declarations page</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>First Named Insured</strong></td><td>First name on Declarations. In commercial policies: has control — can cancel, request changes, is responsible for premiums and reporting losses</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Additional Insured</strong></td><td>Not named on declarations but protected by the policy for a specific interest. Added by endorsement</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- INSURED'S DUTIES AFTER A LOSS -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Insured's Duties After a Loss</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Protect</strong> the damaged property from further damage</li>
            <li><strong>Prepare an inventory</strong> of damaged property</li>
            <li><strong>Cooperate</strong> with the insurer in settling the loss</li>
            <li><strong>Notify the police</strong> in the case of theft</li>
            <li><strong>Submit a signed sworn proof of loss</strong> within the allotted time after being requested</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="highlight">→ Memory: <strong>P.P.C.N.P.</strong> — Protect · Prepare inventory · Cooperate · Notify police · Proof of loss</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- PROVISIONS AND CLAUSES -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Provisions &amp; Clauses</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <table class="notes-table">
            <tr><th>Provision</th><th>What It Means</th></tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Assignment</strong></td>
              <td>Transfer of a legal right or interest in a policy. In P&amp;C, assignments are valid <em>only with prior written consent of the insurer</em></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Appraisal</strong></td>
              <td>If insured and insurer disagree on value of a loss, either party may make a <strong>written demand</strong> for appraisal. Each selects a competent appraiser; if they can't agree, they select an <strong>umpire</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Other Insurance — Pro Rata</strong></td>
              <td>If multiple policies cover the same risk, each pays a pro rata share proportional to its limit vs. total coverage. The insured <strong>cannot collect full amount from each policy</strong> (preserves indemnity)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Notice of Claim</strong></td>
              <td>A form/statement from insured to insurer that events leading to a possible claim have occurred. Includes how, when, and where the loss took place. Can be oral or written initially.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Proof of Loss</strong></td>
              <td>A <strong>sworn written statement</strong> the insured must furnish to the insurer before a loss can be paid. Includes date, description of occurrence, and amount of indemnity claimed. Required <em>near the end</em> of the claims process. Must be in writing — not oral.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Loss Settlement</strong></td>
              <td>Details how a claim will be paid. Options: ACV, Replacement Cost, or Agreed Value. A <strong>consent to settle</strong> provision (found in professional liability) requires the insurer to get the insured's approval before settling for a specific amount.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Cancellation</strong></td>
              <td>Termination of an in-force policy before the expiration date — by either party. Can be voluntary, involuntary, or mutual.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Nonrenewal</strong></td>
              <td>Termination at the expiration date by not offering a continuation or replacement policy.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Mortgagee Rights (Standard Mortgage / Loss Payable Clause)</strong></td>
              <td>
                <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:16px;font-size:0.8rem">
                  <li>Required in all property policies for <strong>real property</strong> (non-movable: houses, structures)</li>
                  <li>Personal property = movable (autos, mobile homes, furniture)</li>
                  <li>Loss paid to insured AND mortgagee per their insurable interest</li>
                  <li>Mortgagee never receives <em>more</em> than their insurable interest (remaining debt)</li>
                  <li>Mortgagee must receive <strong>prior written notice</strong> of cancellation</li>
                  <li>Mortgagee's rights <strong>cannot be defeated</strong> by any act or neglect of the insured</li>
                  <li>Mortgagee rights: sue in own name, pay premiums, submit proof of loss</li>
                </ul>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Salvage</strong></td>
              <td>The amount recovered from the sale of damaged property after a total loss is paid. After paying the total loss, the insurer takes ownership of the damaged property and can sell it to recoup money. Example: insurer pays for totaled car → takes the car → sells for parts.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Arbitration</strong></td>
              <td>Casualty-side equivalent of appraisal. When insurer and insured can't agree on a claim settlement, it's submitted to an arbitrator. <em>Property = Appraisal. Casualty = Arbitration.</em></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Policy Territory</strong></td>
              <td>Defines the geographic location where coverage is provided</td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:10px">→ Key distinction: <strong>Notice of Claim</strong> can be oral or written. <strong>Proof of Loss</strong> must <em>always</em> be in writing (sworn statement).</div>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:8px">→ Real property = non-movable (homes/structures). Personal property = movable (cars, furniture).</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SOURCES OF INSURABILITY / UNDERWRITING -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Sources of Insurability Information</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2);margin-bottom:10px">Insurers use multiple sources to determine insurability. Most require written consent of the insured before use.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Application form</li>
            <li>Motor vehicle records</li>
            <li>Interviews with neighbors, friends, and employers</li>
            <li>Inspection of property</li>
            <li>Inspection of insurance history</li>
          </ul>
          <div style="margin-top:10px;font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2)">Outside reports fall into two categories: <strong style="color:var(--text)">Consumer Reports</strong> and <strong style="color:var(--text)">Investigative Consumer Reports</strong>. Both can only be used by someone with a <em>legitimate business purpose</em> (underwriting, employment screening, credit transactions).</div>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:8px">→ Misrepresentations on the application can void the policy.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAIR CREDIT REPORTING ACT -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA)</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Administered by the <strong>Federal Trade Commission (FTC)</strong></li>
            <li>Establishes procedures consumer-reporting agencies must follow to ensure records are <strong>confidential, accurate, relevant, and properly used</strong></li>
            <li>Protects consumers from circulation of <strong>inaccurate or obsolete</strong> personal or financial information</li>
            <li>Applies to insurance underwriting, employment screening, and credit transactions</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="highlight">→ Exam tip: FCRA = FTC administers it. Protects consumers from FALSE or OBSOLETE financial info.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- GRAMM-LEACH-BLILEY -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (Privacy Protection)</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Insurers <strong>may NOT disclose nonpublic personal information</strong> to a nonaffiliated third party — unless the consumer is clearly notified, given the chance to opt out, and explained how to exercise nondisclosure</li>
            <li>Requires <strong>2 disclosures</strong> to a customer:
              <ol style="margin-top:6px;padding-left:18px;font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2)">
                <li>When the customer relationship is <strong>established</strong> (e.g., policy is purchased)</li>
                <li>Before <strong>disclosing protected information</strong></li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Customer must also receive an <strong>annual privacy disclosure</strong></li>
            <li>Customer has the <strong>right to opt out</strong> — choose not to have private info shared with third parties</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="highlight">→ Key number: <strong>2 disclosures</strong> required. Plus annual notice. Plus right to opt out.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TRIA -->
      <div class="concept open">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">—</span><span class="c-title">Terrorism Risk Insurance Act (TRIA)</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Temporary federal program</strong> — shares the risk of loss from terrorist attacks with the insurance industry</li>
            <li>Requires all <strong>commercial insurers</strong> to offer terrorism coverage</li>
            <li>Federal government reimburses insurers for a portion of paid terrorism losses</li>
            <li>An act of terrorism must be <strong>certified</strong> by: Secretary of the Treasury + Secretary of Homeland Security + Attorney General</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--text);margin:10px 0 6px">Act of Terrorism must:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Be <strong>violent or dangerous</strong> to human life, property, or infrastructure</li>
            <li>Result in damage within the <strong>US</strong> (or to US carriers/vessels/missions)</li>
            <li>Be committed to <strong>coerce</strong> the US civilian population or influence US policy</li>
            <li>Produce P&amp;C insurance losses exceeding a <strong>specified amount</strong></li>
          </ul>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--text);margin:10px 0 6px">TRIA Applies To:</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2)">Commercial property &amp; liability, excess insurance, workers compensation, directors &amp; officers insurance</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--text);margin:10px 0 6px">TRIA Does NOT Apply To (Exclusions):</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2)">Federal/private crop insurance · Private mortgage insurance · Title insurance · Financial guaranty insurance · Medical malpractice · Life &amp; health (including group life) · Federal flood insurance · Reinsurance · Commercial auto · Burglary &amp; theft · Surety · Professional liability (except D&amp;O) · Farm owners multiple peril</p>
          <p style="font-size:0.8rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--text);margin:10px 0 6px">Key Updates:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>2007:</strong> Removed requirement that terrorists act for a foreign interest. $100 billion cap disclosure required to policyholders. Treasury must notify Congress within 15 days if losses exceed $100B.</li>
            <li><strong>2015:</strong> Mandatory recoupment through policyholder surcharges at <strong>140%</strong></li>
            <li><strong>2019 (TRIPRA):</strong> Extended through <strong>December 31, 2027</strong>. Reimbursement fixed at <strong>80%</strong> of covered losses above deductible. Added study requirement on cyberterrorism risks.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="highlight">→ Exam tip: TRIA = temporary federal program. Commercial lines only. Does NOT cover life/health, crop, flood, auto, professional liability (except D&amp;O).</div>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:6px">→ 2019 rate: government reimburses <strong>80%</strong> of covered losses over the deductible.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
