      <!-- Video 1: Insureds -->
      <div class="concept open" style="margin-bottom:10px">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">▶</span><span class="c-title">Video: Insureds</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px">
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(76,175,130,0.12);color:#4caf82;font-weight:700">Ch. 2 — Policy Provisions</span>
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.12);color:var(--amber);font-weight:700">2:15</span>
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2);line-height:1.75;margin:0">
            Different people may be insured under a property and liability policy — not everyone is specifically identified. That's why we have insured designations.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Named Insured</strong> — the individual whose name appears on the policy's declarations page. Generally, whoever purchases the policy (e.g., the homeowner).<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">First Named Insured</strong> — the individual whose name appears <em>first</em> on the declarations. There may be several named insureds, but only one first named insured. Has duties including: paying the premium and giving prompt notice of a claim. Especially important on commercial policies — this is the insurer's primary contact with the business.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Additional Insureds</strong> — individuals or businesses not named on the declarations page, but protected by the policy for a specific financial interest. Added by endorsement. Examples: mortgage company, lienholder on a vehicle.<br><br>
            If a house burns down, the mortgageholder may be entitled to part of the loss payment. If a vehicle is totaled with an outstanding loan, the insurance company pays off the lender first. This ensures the correct parties get paid when a loss occurs.
          </p>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:12px">→ Key exam point: Additional insureds are added by <strong>endorsement</strong>. They have a specific financial interest — like a lender or lienholder.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video 2: Binders & Subrogation -->
      <div class="concept open" style="margin-bottom:10px">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">▶</span><span class="c-title">Video: Binders and Subrogation</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px">
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(76,175,130,0.12);color:#4caf82;font-weight:700">Ch. 2 — Policy Provisions</span>
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.12);color:var(--amber);font-weight:700">1:43</span>
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2);line-height:1.75;margin:0">
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Binders</strong> — A binder is a temporary agreement (written or oral) providing coverage until a policy can be issued. It gives the insured <em>immediate temporary coverage</em>. Binders expire once the policy is issued or after a set number of days (varies by state). The effective date equals the date the binder was issued. If the policy is declined, the binder expires the day after receipt of the cancellation notice.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Subrogation</strong> — The legal right of the insurance company to seek damages from a third party <em>after</em> it has reimbursed the insured for a loss.<br><br>
            Example: You're in a hit-and-run accident. Your insurer pays your claim and repairs your vehicle. When you accept the claim check, you transfer your right to seek reimbursement from the other driver to the insurance company. The insurer can then sue the at-fault party to recover the amount paid.
          </p>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:12px">→ Subrogation: insured gets paid first → insured signs over their right to collect from the third party → insurer pursues the third party. Prevents double recovery.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video 3: Policy Structure -->
      <div class="concept open" style="margin-bottom:10px">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">▶</span><span class="c-title">Video: Policy Structure</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px">
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(76,175,130,0.12);color:#4caf82;font-weight:700">Ch. 2 — Policy Provisions</span>
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.12);color:var(--amber);font-weight:700">3:09</span>
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2);line-height:1.75;margin:0">
            The <strong style="color:var(--text)">Insurance Services Office (ISO)</strong> creates standardized P&amp;C insurance forms adopted by individual states. This is why policies from two different companies look very similar.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Declarations ("dec page")</strong> — First section. Who is the insurer? Who is the insured? What property is covered? What are the limits? What is the premium?<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Definitions</strong> — Clarifies terms. Bold, italic, or quoted words are defined here.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Insuring Agreement</strong> — Spells out the insurer's obligation to provide coverage. Lists parties, effective/renewal dates, coverage description, and perils. The insured promises to pay premium; the insurer promises to pay covered claims.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Additional/Supplementary Coverages</strong> — Extra coverage for specific loss expenses, usually at no additional premium.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Conditions</strong> — Rules both parties follow. Includes: insurer's right to inspect, how policy may be changed, refund processing if cancelled early.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Endorsements</strong> — Written addendums changing the policy. Must be in writing, attached to policy, signed by executive officer. Used to add/delete coverage or correct info.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Exclusions</strong> — What is NOT covered. Can exclude people, property, or perils.
          </p>
          <div style="margin-top:14px;padding:12px 16px;background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(232,146,58,0.12),rgba(155,127,199,0.08));border:1.5px solid rgba(232,146,58,0.3);border-radius:var(--r2)">
            <div style="font-size:0.7rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.6px;margin-bottom:6px">💡 Exam Acronym from Video</div>
            <p style="font-size:0.88rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--text);margin:0;letter-spacing:1px"><strong style="color:var(--amber)">D</strong>eclarations &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong style="color:var(--amber)">I</strong>nsuring Agreement &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong style="color:var(--amber)">C</strong>onditions &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong style="color:var(--amber)">E</strong>xclusions</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.78rem;color:var(--text2);margin:6px 0 0"><strong style="color:var(--text)">DICE</strong> — the major components of any P&amp;C policy</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video 4: Common Policy Provisions -->
      <div class="concept open" style="margin-bottom:10px">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">▶</span><span class="c-title">Video: Common Policy Provisions</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px">
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(76,175,130,0.12);color:#4caf82;font-weight:700">Ch. 2 — Policy Provisions</span>
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.12);color:var(--amber);font-weight:700">4:17</span>
          </div>
          <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--text2);line-height:1.75;margin:0">
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Appraisal vs. Arbitration</strong> — Both mean the same thing: when the insurer and insured can't agree on a claim, a written request brings in a third party to settle the dispute. In <em>property</em> claims each party selects an appraiser. In <em>casualty</em> claims it goes to an arbitrator.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Assignment</strong> — Transfer of rights or interest in a policy to someone else. Only valid with prior written consent of the insurer.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Other Insurance</strong> — When an insured has multiple policies on the same property, losses are shared proportionally among the insurers.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Notice of Claim</strong> — When the insured calls and reports a loss. The insurer must acknowledge receipt, provide forms/instructions/assistance, and begin investigation.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Proof of Loss</strong> — When the insured completes, signs, and submits the claim form. This is the sworn proof of loss.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Liberalization Clause</strong> — If the insurer improves coverage on new policies at no extra premium, ALL current policyholders get those same improved benefits immediately — no waiting for renewal.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Subrogation</strong> — When the insured accepts a claim payment, they waive their right to seek damages from the at-fault third party and give that right to the insurer. Based on the principle of indemnity — prevents the insured from collecting twice.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Salvage</strong> — The amount recovered from the sale of damaged property after a total loss is paid. The insurer abandons interest to the insured and takes the right to salvage. Example: after paying a totaled car claim, the insurer takes the car and sells it for parts to recoup money.<br><br>
            <strong style="color:var(--text)">Third Party Provisions</strong> — Protect interests of parties like mortgagees. A third party's right to recover is limited to their insurable interest. Third parties must receive written advance notice if a policy is cancelled or nonrenewed.
          </p>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:12px">→ Appraisal = <strong>property</strong> disputes. Arbitration = <strong>casualty</strong> disputes. Same concept, different sides.</div>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:8px">→ Salvage: total loss paid → insurer <strong>takes ownership</strong> of the damaged property and sells it. That's how they recoup part of the payout.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video 5: Cancellation vs. Nonrenewal -->
      <div class="concept open" style="margin-bottom:10px">
        <div class="concept-hdr" onclick="toggleConcept(this)"><div class="concept-hdr-l"><span class="c-emoji">▶</span><span class="c-title">Video: Cancellation vs. Nonrenewal</span></div><span class="c-arrow">▼</span></div>
        <div class="concept-body">
          <div style="display:flex;gap:10px;flex-wrap:wrap;margin-bottom:12px">
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(76,175,130,0.12);color:#4caf82;font-weight:700">Ch. 2 — Policy Provisions</span>
            <span style="font-size:0.7rem;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:20px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.12);color:var(--amber);font-weight:700">1:45</span>
          </div>
          <table class="notes-table">
            <tr><th></th><th style="color:var(--amber)">Cancellation</th><th style="color:var(--purple)">Nonrenewal</th></tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>When</strong></td>
              <td>BEFORE the expiration date — early termination while policy is still in force</td>
              <td>AT the expiration date — coverage simply ends at the end of the policy period</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Who can do it</strong></td>
              <td>Insured (any time, written request) OR Insurer (limited reasons)</td>
              <td>Either party chooses not to continue</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Insurer's valid reasons</strong></td>
              <td>Nonpayment of premium · Material misrepresentation · Substantial change in risk</td>
              <td>No restriction — insurer just doesn't offer a renewal</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Notice required</strong></td>
              <td>Yes — insurer must always provide <strong>advance written notice</strong> to insured</td>
              <td>Yes — advance notice also required</td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <div style="margin-top:12px;padding:12px 14px;background:rgba(232,146,58,0.08);border:1px solid rgba(232,146,58,0.25);border-radius:var(--r2)">
            <div style="font-size:0.7rem;font-weight:800;color:var(--amber);text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.6px;margin-bottom:6px">Example from Video</div>
            <p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--text2);margin:0;line-height:1.7">12-month policy: Jan 1 – Dec 31.<br>
            Terminated on <strong>March 15</strong> = <strong style="color:var(--amber)">Cancellation</strong> (before Dec 31 expiration).<br>
            Coverage ends on <strong>Dec 31</strong> and not renewed = <strong style="color:var(--purple)">Nonrenewal</strong> (at expiration date).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="highlight" style="margin-top:10px">→ One-line rule: <strong>Cancellation = ends EARLY. Nonrenewal = ends ON TIME.</strong></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

