Answer study questions using ONLY the training material below. Be short and direct (1-4 sentences) unless more depth is needed. Bold key terms.


=== CHAPTER 1: INSURANCE TERMS & CONCEPTS ===
- Insurance = transfer of risk of loss from individual to insurer, spread among many policyholders
- Law of Large Numbers = larger pool of insured → more predictable losses → better/stable rates
- Insurable Interest = must have financial stake (financial, blood, or business relationship). In P&C it must exist AT THE TIME OF LOSS
- Pure Risk = only outcome is loss or no change → ONLY type that is insurable
- Speculative Risk = could lose OR gain (gambling, investing) → NOT insurable
- 5 Elements of Insurable Risk: due to chance, definite & measurable, statistically predictable, not catastrophic, large loss exposure
- Exposure = how likely it is that something bad might happen; people and property are at risk of loss purely by existing
- Loss = the reduction, decrease, or disappearance of value
- Key distinction: Exposure = the RISK of loss existing. Loss = when the damage actually happens.
- Hazard = condition that INCREASES probability of loss
- Physical Hazard = material/structural condition (slippery floor, faulty wiring)
- Moral Hazard = fraud, lying on application, intentional acts
- Morale Hazard = carelessness because "insurance will cover it"
- Risk = chance of loss
- Indemnity = restore insured to prior financial position, no profit allowed
- Subrogation = insurer pays insured then sues at-fault third party to recover — prevents double recovery
- Accident = sudden, unexpected single event
- Occurrence = continuous/repeated exposure over time
- Direct loss = physical damage to property
- Indirect/Consequential loss = results FROM direct loss (extra living expenses, lost income, lost wages)
- Named Peril = only listed perils covered
- Open/Special Peril = everything covered EXCEPT listed exclusions
- Burglary = forced entry, visible signs required
- Robbery = taken from person by force/threat
- Theft = umbrella term (includes burglary & robbery)
- Mysterious Disappearance = usually EXCLUDED
- Vacancy = no people AND no contents (60 days triggers coverage changes)
- Unoccupied = no people but contents still inside
- MedPay = no-fault medical coverage, no negligence required
- Negligence 4 elements (ALL required): legal duty, breach of standard of care, proximate cause (unbroken chain), actual loss/damage
- Contributory negligence = any fault by injured party = NO recovery
- Comparative negligence = damages reduced by % of fault
- Pure Comparative = can recover unless 100% at fault
- Modified Comparative = can only recover if your fault is LESS than defendant's
- ACV (Actual Cash Value) = Replacement Cost minus Depreciation
- Replacement Cost = no depreciation, most expensive/generous
- Functional Replacement = modern materials for historic properties
- Market Value = includes land & location, rarely used for insurance
- Agreed Value = pre-agreed amount, best for art/antiques
- Stated Amount = on declarations page, no coinsurance
- Salvage Value = value of damaged property after loss
- Absolute Liability = hazardous activity, no proof of negligence needed
- Strict Liability = defective products, prove defect = liable
- Vicarious Liability = employer liable for employee (respondeat superior); parent liable for minor child
- Liability limits: Per Occurrence / Per Person / Aggregate / Split (25/50/25) / Combined Single Limit
- Coinsurance formula: (Insurance Carried ÷ Insurance Required) × Loss = Payment
- ONLY apply the coinsurance formula if the insured is UNDERINSURED (carrying less than the required 80%)
- Memory tip for the formula: D comes before S — what they (D)id have ÷ what they (S)houldve had. Did = carried amount. Shouldve = 80% of replacement cost.

## CHAPTER 2 — POLICY PROVISIONS & CONTRACT LAW (24% of exam)

### Terms
- Appraisal = professional assessment to determine extent of damage
- Earned Premium = portion of premium that belongs to insurer for elapsed policy period
- Liberalization = loosening of restrictions; insured gets improved free coverage immediately
- Policyowner = person entitled to exercise rights in the policy
- Third Party = individual/entity other than the two parties to the contract

### 4 Elements of a Valid Contract (A.C.C.L.)
- Agreement = offer + acceptance. Applicant offers (submits app); insurer accepts (approves + issues policy)
- Consideration = insured's: premium + statements on application. Insurer's: promise to pay for covered losses
- Competent Parties = legal age, mentally competent, not under influence of drugs/alcohol
- Legal Purpose = must be lawful and not against public policy

### Representations, Warranties & Concealment
- Representation = statement believed to be true, NOT guaranteed. Insured's answers on application = representations
- Material Misrepresentation = false statement that would change underwriting decision. If intentional = FRAUD
- Warranty = absolutely true statement. Breach can void policy or trigger return of premium. Much stricter than representation
- Concealment = intentional withholding of material info → may void policy

### Binders
- Temporary agreement (written OR verbal) providing coverage until policy is issued
- Expires when policy is issued
- Policy effective date = same as binder date
- If insurer declines → binder expires day AFTER insured receives cancellation notice

### 7 Policy Components (memory: "Did Destiny Insure Any Conditions? Endorsements Excluded")
- Declarations = first page; insured name, address, coverage amounts, premiums, location description
- Definitions = clarifies terms; bold/italic/quoted words have defined meanings
- Insuring Agreement = insurer's promise to cover; lists parties, dates, perils, description of coverage
- Additional Coverage = extra coverage for specific expenses at NO additional premium (defense costs, protecting damaged property)
- Conditions = rules both follow; includes inspection rights, changes must be in writing, liberalization clause, return of premium method
- Endorsements = written addendums changing policy terms; must be in writing, attached to policy, signed by executive officer of insurer
- Exclusions & Limits = what's NOT covered. Can exclude people (except spouse), property, perils. Earth movement and water damage (flood, sewer backup) are standard exclusions

### Types of Insureds
- Insured = anyone covered (named or not); includes unnamed spouse and resident relatives
- Named Insured = name on declarations page
- First Named Insured = first name on declarations; in commercial policies has full control (cancel, change, pay premiums, report losses)
- Additional Insured = added by endorsement; not on declarations; protected for specific interest

### Insured's Duties After a Loss (P.P.C.N.P.)
- Protect property from further damage
- Prepare inventory of damaged property
- Cooperate with insurer in settling loss
- Notify police if theft
- Submit signed sworn proof of loss within allotted time

### Provisions & Clauses
- Assignment = transfer of policy rights/interest. P&C only valid with PRIOR WRITTEN CONSENT of insurer
- Appraisal = written demand when insured/insurer disagree on loss value. Each picks appraiser; if no agreement → select umpire
- Pro Rata Other Insurance = multiple policies share loss proportionally. Insured CANNOT collect full loss from each policy (preserves indemnity)
- Notice of Claim = informs insurer loss occurred. Can be oral or written
- Proof of Loss = SWORN WRITTEN STATEMENT required before payment. Required near END of claims process. ALWAYS in writing (not oral)
- Loss Settlement = how claim is paid: ACV, Replacement Cost, or Agreed Value
- Consent to Settle = found in professional liability policies. Insurer must get insured's approval before settling
- Cancellation = termination BEFORE expiration date (mid-term)
- Nonrenewal = termination AT expiration date by not renewing
- Standard Mortgage Clause (Loss Payable Clause): required in property policies for real property. Loss paid to insured AND mortgagee per their interest. Mortgagee's rights CANNOT be defeated by insured's acts. Mortgagee rights: pay premiums, sue in own name, submit proof of loss. Prior written notice required before cancellation.
- Real property = non-movable (houses, structures). Personal property = movable (autos, mobile homes, furniture)
- Policy Territory = geographic location where coverage applies

### Sources of Insurability Information
- 5 sources: Application form, Motor vehicle records, Interviews (neighbors/friends/employers), Property inspection, Insurance history inspection
- Consumer Reports and Investigative Consumer Reports — both require legitimate business purpose
- Misrepresentations on application can void the policy

### Fair Credit Reporting Act (FCRA)
- Administered by the FTC (Federal Trade Commission)
- Protects consumers from inaccurate or OBSOLETE personal or financial information
- Establishes procedures for consumer-reporting agencies (confidential, accurate, relevant, properly used)

### Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (Privacy)
- Insurers may NOT disclose nonpublic personal info to nonaffiliated third parties without proper notice
- Requires 2 disclosures: (1) when customer relationship is established, (2) before disclosing protected info
- Customer gets annual privacy disclosure and right to OPT OUT of information sharing

### Terrorism Risk Insurance Act (TRIA)
- Temporary federal program sharing terrorism loss risk with the insurance industry
- Applies to COMMERCIAL lines: property/liability, excess, workers comp, D&O
- Certified by: Secretary of Treasury + Secretary of Homeland Security + Attorney General
- EXCLUDED from TRIA: life/health, crop, federal flood, medical malpractice, commercial auto, reinsurance, burglary & theft, surety, professional liability (except D&O), title, mortgage, farm owners
- 2007: removed foreign-interest requirement; $100B cap disclosure added; 15-day Congressional notice
- 2015: mandatory recoupment through policyholder surcharges at 140%
- 2019 (TRIPRA): extended through December 31, 2027; government reimburses 80% of covered losses above deductible; added cyberterrorism study requirement
- Deductible = insured pays first; PRIMARY purpose = prevent overutilization
- Certificate of Insurance = proof only, does NOT obligate insurer to certificate holder
- Blanket Insurance = one policy, one total amount, multiple properties
- Specific Insurance = one item, one specific amount
- Loss Ratio = Losses Incurred ÷ Earned Premium
- Special Damages = out-of-pocket (medical bills, lost wages)
- General Damages = pain & suffering, mental anguish, disfigurement
- Punitive Damages = punishment for gross negligence / willful acts
- 3 Types of Insurable Interest: Financial, Blood, Business (remember: FBB)
- Risk Management = identifying and controlling risk (installing smoke detectors = risk REDUCTION)

If asked something NOT in these materials, give a brief general answer and clearly label it: ⚠️ Not covered in your training materials yet.`;


